I have recently started using Selenium 2 to automate the testing of a .NET web application that I am currently working on with the end goal to execute a test suite to automate the testing of this web application as part of a nightly build.  Selenium 2 provides a very intuitive API, allowing you to write tests to mimic a users actions within a browser.

The website I was testing makes quite a few AJAX calls, which more often than not resulted in either showing additional elements on a page or removing elements triggered by a user driven action such as clicking on a button or a link.

Testing AJAX requests poses a problem because Selenium 2 does not know that when I click on a button whether an AJAX request will be made or not.  This means Selenium does not know whether to wait for a response from the AJAX request before continuing to execute the rest of the current test.

The simple way around this is to include a Thread.Sleep command to halt the execution of the test for a few seconds allowing the display to be updated before commencing with the test to test for the result of the AJAX call.  This can begin to get messy and can result in inconsistent test results based on whether the action completed within the allocated time frame.  At the other end of the spectrum, if you set the Sleep time to high, your tests may take a long time to run!  

Common alternatives are to simply poll the page in a loop checking whether the element has been displayed.

The Selenium 2 framework provides a WebDriverWait class.  This class effectively wraps the polling of the page for us.  The WebDriverWait class includes an Until method, which accepts a single Func<IWebDriver, IWebElement> as its parameter.  This can be used to instruct Selenium to wait until the chosen element is found on the page, halting execution of the test until it is either found or the specified time out is reached.  An example is shown below:

[sourcecode language="csharp"]

public class WaitFor
    {
        public static void ElementPresent(IWebDriver driver, By locator, TimeSpan timespan)
        {
            IWait<IWebDriver> wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, timespan);
            wait.Until(d => d.FindElement(locator));
        }
    }

[/sourcecode]

As of the time of writing Selenium 2 is in beta 3.  You can download Selenium 2 from <a href="http://seleniumhq.org/download/">here </a> and get started with the quick start guide from <a href="http://seleniumhq.org/docs/03_webdriver.html">here</a>

NServiceBus supports three profiles out of the box, Lite, Integration and Production. Dependent on which profile you have set at startup, NServiceBus will run with a different setup, i.e. writing to memory in Lite or a database in production.

Regardless of which profile you are running the same functionality is expected. This is where custom profiles come in. Custom profiles enables the ability to alter segments of functionality based on the profile you are running in. This is achieved by creating a class that implements the IHandleProfile<T> interface, where T is either NServiceBus.Lite, NServiceBus.Integration, or NServiceBus.Production. For example

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
class LiteIntegrationPointBehavior : IHandleProfile<NServiceBus.Lite>
{
    public void ProfileActivated()
    {
        // return a stub response
    }
}

class ProductionIntegrationPointBehavior : IHandleProfile<NServiceBus.Production>
{
    public void ProfileActivated()
    {
        // call the real service
    }
}
[/sourcecode]

An area where this feature would prove invaluable is during testing.  A project  I am currently working on interacts with a number of third party integration points for the system to operate end to end.  This causes problems for our integration test suite, which are executed as part of the nightly build.  We do not want to have to rely on a third party's system provide a testing interface or even for the service to be available, to ensure our tests all go green. So rather than sending a message to an endpoint, we can simply configure our injected profile to not call the service and return a fake valid response.  This means we can still test are core code, don't have to build stub services and we also would not need to change the config of the standard setup for the sake of the test suite.

<a href="http://www.nservicebus.com/Profiles.aspx"> Read more about profiles on the NServiceBus website</a>

One of the many benefits that the ASP.NET MVC framework has brought to .NET web development over traditional ASP.NET web forms is the separation of the UI's HTML markup and the code behind with the introduction of strongly typed views and controllers.  

This separation has made it very straight forward to test all actions within a controller with unit tests.  However there have always been some web specific elements which have been difficult to test, particularly when an action is making use of the either the current HttpContext, stateful values with the session and values which form part of the QueryString to name a few.  A common approach would be add some munge to your tests to mock out these HTTP objects to allow you to test your actions.  There is also commonly an element of repetitive code when testing the result of a controller action, such as was the right view returned with the right model etc.

This leads us on to the MvcContrib project.  MvcContrib is a set of helper libraries, which simplify not only testing but also writing ASP.NET MVC applications.  For the purpose of this blog post we are going to focus on MvcContrib.TestProject.  This library provides a number of very useful extensions methods for testing, which are applied to the controllers, actions and models

<strong>Getting started</strong>

To get started, you can add the library to your project using NuGet, with the following command

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
INSTALL-PACKAGE MvcContrib.Mvc3.TestHelper-ci
[/sourcecode]

Jumping straight into the code, the first thing to do is to initialise the test controller factory with an instance of your controller.  Initialising your controller with the TestControllerBuilder provides access to all the controller and action extensions.  An example of initialising a HomeController with the test controller factory is shown below.

[sourcecode language="csharp"]

[TestInitialize]
public void Setup()
{
    controllerBuilder = new TestControllerBuilder();
    controller = new HomeController(mockTasks.Object);
    controllerBuilder.InitializeController(controller);
}

[/sourcecode]

Using the instance of the TestControllerBuilder we just created above, it is now possible to set objects such as in the following example, session, querystring, temp data and cache data for use within the controller tests.

[sourcecode language="csharp"]

[TestMethod]
public void set_test_state_example()
{
    controllerBuilder.Session["Username"] = "Devscrum";
    controllerBuilder.QueryString.Add("Category", "blogs");
    controllerBuilder.TempDataDictionary["Message"] = "Any old message";
    controllerBuilder.HttpContext.Cache["Cachy"] = "Something to cache";

    controller.Index();
}

[/sourcecode]

MvcContrib provides a lot more than just a nice easy way to mock HTTP request data, it also provides a means to simplify testing the results from calling controller actions.  These extensions are added to any type that inherits from ActionResult and include things such as testing whether a partial view or a regular view is returned, the type of the model returned to name but two.

[sourcecode language="csharp"]

[TestMethod]
public void test_view_and_model()
{
    var result = controller.Index();
    var model = result.AssertPartialViewRendered().WithViewData<HomeViewModel>();
    model.Name.ShouldBe("Devscrum");
}

[/sourcecode]

The AssertPartialViewRendered does exactly what it says, it asserts that a partial view has been rendered, where as the WithViewData asserts that a model of type HomeViewModel has been returned as the model.  MvcContrib even adds extensions to the model properties.  This is demostrated above with the inclusion of the ShouldBe extension on my Name property from the HomeViewModel.

Testing routes is also greatly simplified with MvcContrib.  Take the following example.

[sourcecode language="csharp"]

[TestMethod]
public void test_redirect()
{
    var result = controller.Login();
    result.AssertActionRedirect().ToAction<AccountController>(x => x.Index());
}

[/sourcecode]

I would seriously recommend checking MvcContrib.  The best place to start is on the MvcContrib site on codeplex, which you can find <a href="http://mvccontrib.codeplex.com/">here</a>

I recently had the requirement on a ASP.NET MVC project that I have been working on, to periodically check an external data source for any new data to update my local data source.  To achieve this I thought about perhaps writing a windows service or even writing my own custom code using a timer, but after a short search me old mate google led me straight to a cracking utility called Quartz.NET.

Quartz.NET is an enterprise job scheduler for the .NET platform.  Quartz provides a framework for creating scheduled jobs and triggers where you can set the frequency of the execution of these jobs.  Using Quartz is simple!  Quartz provides a scheduler, which is responsible for managing the execution of registered jobs.  To schedule a job you have to create a JobDetail and a Trigger.  To create a JobDetail you need to create a custom class which inherits from the IJob interface.  This interface provides a single method Execute.

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
void Execute(JobExecutionContext context)
[/sourcecode]

The trigger specifies the time interval on when to execute a job.  Quartz.NET provides a number of different triggers, such as the simple trigger which can be configured to run every hour, every day etc, or a Cron trigger which provides more advanced options for executing a job such as the first sunday of every month, or every 10 minutes between 10:00am and 11:00am, on Monday, Wednesday and Friday's.  These triggers should meet any scheduler requirement.  The sample below shows the scheduling of a single job on a simple trigger that is executed once a day at 23:59. 

[sourcecode language="csharp"]

private void StartScheduler()
{
     ISchedulerFactory schedulerFactory = new StdSchedulerFactory();

     IScheduler scheduler = schedulerFactory.GetScheduler();
     scheduler.Start();

     JobDetail championshipDownloader = new JobDetail("ResultExtractor", null, typeof(ChampionshipJob));

     Trigger trigger = TriggerUtils.MakeDailyTrigger(23, 59);
     trigger.StartTimeUtc = DateTime.UtcNow;
     trigger.Name = "Daily Trigger";

     scheduler.ScheduleJob(championshipDownloader, trigger);
}

[/sourcecode]

This initialisation code is specified within the global.asax Application_Start method.  

The following code sample shows the basic implementation of a Job.  Any code within the execute method will be executed when the job is triggered.  All Job's take a JobExecutionContext as an input parameter.  The JobExecutionContext provides the ability to pass any custom parameters into a Job, which can be set when creating the schedule.  The custom parameters can be extracted as a JobDataMap as show below.

[sourcecode language="csharp"]

public class ChampionshipJob : IJob
{
     private static ILog _log = LogManager.GetLogger(typeof(ChampionshipJob));

     public ChampionshipJob()
     {
     }

     public void Execute(JobExecutionContext context)
     {
          JobDataMap dataMap = context.JobDetail.JobDataMap;
          string jobSays = dataMap.GetString("CustomStringParameter");

          //Perform some operation
     }
} 

[/sourcecode]

I would very much recommend having a look at Quartz.NET if you need any code written in .NET to be executed on a scheduler.  To download the Quartz.NET binaries and for further information including an excellent tutorial, take a look at the <a href="http://quartznet.sourceforge.net/index.html">Quartz.NET site</a>

Microsoft WCF Data Services provides a means to access a data source, such as a database directly over the web by issuing commands within the URI. These commands include all the the usual CRUD operations.  WCF Data Service uses the Open Data Protocol, referred to as OData as its web protocol for sharing data.  OData messages can take the format of well known formats such as Atom or JSON.

datajs is a JavaScript library which simplifies sending requests and handling responses against OData services, such as a WCF Data Service.  datajs can natively understand how to read OData messages returned from a data service as it knows how to deserialize the response typically in the format of an Atom feed into a flattened object, which can then be used directly within JavaScript.  

datajs also provides the ability to make cross-domain requests by using the JSONP with OData.  JSONP (JavaScript Object Notation with Padding) allows you to load data located on another domain by passing a JSON response from the server, wrapping it in a user specified callback function.  JSONP requires that both your request and response handle JSONP.  

You can get datajs via NuGet with the following command.

<blockquote>INSTALL-PACKAGE Datajs</blockquote>

Ok, so that's a bit of background and quite a few acronyms for you, what I wanted to show you is how easy it is to start making use of an WCF Data Service direct from the browser.  The default provider for a WCF Data Service is an Entity Framework context, however for the sake of this post I've added a WCF Data Service to my Visual Studio solution using an in-memory data source with the reflection provider, which allows me to expose my in memory objects directly through the data service.  In the code sample below the provider exposes a single entity 'Question' as an IQueryable entity.  The code for this data service is as follows.

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
namespace SampleDataService
{
    public class DataService : DataService<QuestionItemData>
    {
        // This method is called only once to initialize service-wide policies.
        public static void InitializeService(DataServiceConfiguration config)
        {
            config.SetEntitySetAccessRule("*", EntitySetRights.All);
            config.UseVerboseErrors = true;
            config.DataServiceBehavior.MaxProtocolVersion = DataServiceProtocolVersion.V2;
        }
    }

    [DataServiceKeyAttribute("QuestionId")]
    public class Question
    {
        public string QuestionId { get; set; }
        public string Label { get; set; }
        public string Value { get; set; }
    }

    public class QuestionItemData
    {
        private static IList<Question> questions;

        static QuestionItemData()
        {
            questions = new Question[]
            {
                new Question { QuestionId = "1", Label = "Trade", Value = "Plumber" },
                new Question { QuestionId = "2", Label = "Employement", Value = "Umemployed" }
            };
        }

        public IQueryable<Question> Questions
        {
            get { return questions.AsQueryable<Question>(); }
        }
    }
}
[/sourcecode]

As previously mentioned you can query a data service through the URI as it is truely RESTful.  Say I wanted to return the first question I can filter my request with the following URI syntax by directly executing it in the browser address bar.

<blockquote>http://localhost:58641/DataService.svc/Questions?$filter=QuestionId eq '1'</blockquote>


<a href="http://blog.devscrum.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/DataService-Questions.png"><img src="http://blog.devscrum.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/DataService-Questions.png" alt="issuing a filter command against a data service entity" title="DataService-Questions" width="630" height="612" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-289" /></a>

The response above is returned as an Atom feed, which is the default format unless otherwise stated.  datajs understands the Atom feed format and removes the need for you to parse the response client side.

As an example of using datajs within a web page. Having added a reference to the data.js library, I can then use it to call my data service within JavaScript.  The code below queries my data service to return all the questions, it also specifies that the response is returned as JSONP.  The server will also need to permit this, which can be handled by adding a custom IDispatchMessageInspector and applying it as an attribute of the data service.  Google JSONPSupportInspector for an example.

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
function PollQuestions() {
       OData.defaultHttpClient.enableJsonpCallback = true;
       OData.defaultHttpClient.formatQueryString = '$format=json';
       OData.read("http://localhost/dataservice.svc/Questions", function (data, response) {

       alert(data.results);
   });
}
[/sourcecode]

It is as simple as that!  You can issue not only GET requests but also POST and DELETE requests to change the data within your data source if permissions are provided

For more information on datajs please take a look at the datajs site on codeplex <a href="http://datajs.codeplex.com/">here</a>

The publish / subscription pattern is a messaging pattern where messages are broadcast by a publisher and are pushed to a variable number of subscribers who have subscribed to the service. The pattern provides loose coupling by disconnecting the publishers from its subscribers commonly over the form of a queue.

SignalR is an asynchronous signalling library for ASP.NET which provides a framework for broadcasting messages to multiple clients when a given operation on the server is executed, providing a publish / subscription model with the subscribers being either a .NET client application or a web page.  SignalR can be used to keep a number of web clients in sync with each other at real time with data held on the server. SignalR achieves this by holding open both the client and server side connections, ensuring the connection always stays open.  When a message is sent from a client to the server the server side operation can broadcast a response to all clients by sending a callback to all the open client connections.

SignalR provides a far more efficient solution than simply making a client continuously poll the server on a set timer to check for any change to the state held on the the server and keep itself in sync.  SignalR provides an architecture for pushing messages to listening clients rather than having each client individually responsible for pulling messages from the server.  This can dramatically reduce the load on the server ensuring there are no needless requests repeatedly being sent from clients.

The real beauty of SignalR is in its simplicity.  Requests are sent direct from a web view using JavaScript to the server, and responses are received via a callback on an open connection.  This means that SignalR can be used with frameworks such as Knockout.js for easily keeping the UI refreshed with the latest data.

I am sure you can already think of a number of situations where this can be very useful. Such examples could include either an online chat application or a real time booking system.  However I found that SignalR was the answer to a problem I had been looking to solve for a while.  I am currently working on a large web based integration project for placing insurance quotes online.  For a single request that is submitted for a quote, that request can be sent to multiple third party endpoints for processing.  All requests are sent asynchronously from the client to the server.  Within the application I have a health check routine, which monitors the status of these endpoints.  I want to use SignalR to broadcast a message informing the user of the status of a given service within a footer on the application.  This will inform the customer who may be waiting on an insurance quote if a service ever goes offline.  This will also be very useful during development.

Lets walk through how this could be accomplished by creating a server side endpoint that will be responsible for receiving a request from a client, change a data object and then be responsible for issuing a response with that change to multiple clients.

First create a new ASP.NET MVC 3 web application. To add SignalR to this solution you can issue the following NuGet command in the package manager console within Visual Studio.

<blockquote>Install-Package SignalR</blockquote>

This will download and add the following scripts to your solution.

<ul>
	<li>Scripts/jquery-1.6.4.js</li>
	<li>Scripts/jquery.signalR.js</li>
</ul>

plus minimised versions of both scripts. 

It will also add a assembly reference to SignalR.dll in your project 

There are two options for implementing SignalR server-side.  Both options involve deriving a class from an object within the SignalR framework.  The two options are persistent connections and hubs.  So what is the difference I hear you ask?  Well let's take a quick look at both.

A persistent connection endpoint is exposed as an IHttpHandler.  This allows the endpoint to be accessed over HTTP, however in order to do so you must add a custom route map into the route map collection within the web applications global.asax.  Deriving from a PersistentConnection enables the ability to override a number of set operations within the SignalR framework to receive client requests and broadcast responses.

The other option is to use a hub.  A hub provides the ability to send different types of messages between client and server.  There is no need to create a custom route map when using hubs.  All requests are routed through the /signalr/hubs route which is added by the SignalR framework to access the hubs.  Hubs allow you to add any operations you like.  In this example we are going to use Hubs. 

The code below is a simple implementation of a hub, with two methods GetServiceState() and UpdateServiceState(), both of which are exposed over HTTP and can be called direct from JavaScript running in a browser.  The code includes a static member variable called messages.  This is a list of strings and it is static so that its state can be shared across all client instances. The intention of the first method GetServiceState is set the initial state on the client.  It is called when the client first opens a connection to the hub.  The single line of the method uses the Clients object, which is a dynamic object which represents all the connected clients.  As this object is dynamic you can  simply specify the name of the callback routine that the JavaScript clients will be listening on.  This single line allows you to push the messages collection to all connected clients.  The second method UpdateServiceState adds an item to the list and pushes it out to all clients.  In this example the current date and time is added to the list.

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
public class HealthCheck : Hub
{
    public static List<string> messages = new List<string>();

    public void GetServiceState()
    {
        Clients.updateMessages(messages);
    }

    public void UpdateServiceState()
    {
        messages.Add(DateTime.Now.ToString("dd/MM/yyyy HH:mm:ss"));

        Clients.updateMessages(messages);
    }
}
[/sourcecode]

So now to set up the client.  In the _Layout,cshtml within your MVC 3 project add a script reference to the SignalR JavaScript library that was downloaded and added to the scripts folder when SignalR was added to the solution with NuGet. Please note that SignalR requires jquery to also be enabled. Therefore you will need to add the following two references. 

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
<script src="@Url.Content("~/Scripts/jquery-1.6.4.min.js")" type="text/javascript"></script>
<script src="@Url.Content("~/Scripts/jquery.signalr.min.js")" type="text/javascript"></script>
[/sourcecode]

In index.cshtml add the following code

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
<script src="/signalr/hubs" type="text/javascript"></script>
<script type="text/javascript">
    $(function () {
        // creates a proxy to the health check hub
        var healthCheckHub = $.connection.healthCheck;

        // handles the callback sent from the server
        healthCheckHub.updateMessages = function (data) {
            $("li").remove();

            $.each(data, function () {
                $('#messages').append('<li>' + this + '</li>');
            });
        };

        $("#trigger").click(function () {
            healthCheckHub.updateServiceState();
        });

        // Start the connection and request current state
        $.connection.hub.start(function () {
            healthCheckHub.getServiceState();
        });
    });
</script>

<ul id="messages"></ul>

<button type="button" id="trigger">Send request</button>
[/sourcecode]

The code above creates a proxy reference to the health check hub, it registers a callback called updateMessages.  This callback is the one that the dynamic Clients object makes reference to and broadcast messages on. An event handler is added for the button.  This will call the UpdateServiceState method on the hub when the button is clicked. Finally a connection to the hub is made and the GetServiceState method is called to retrieve the initial server state when the page is first rendered.  

To test open two browser tabs and navigate to the view in both.  Now click on the Send request button in one of the tabs and you will find that the current date and time is displayed shortly afterwards.  Now flip to the other tab and you'll see that the date and time displayed in the first tab is also displayed.  This is because when you clicked the button in the first tab, the hub was called, the current date and time was added to the messages collection and this collection was pushed out to all listening clients who have an open connection registered, in this case both of the tabs.

So this is pretty clever but not a very useful example, but none the less it shows demonstrates a lot of the required plumbing, as we have made a connection to the hub and have registered a callback so that when a message is added on the hub it can be picked up and displayed by any listening clients with an open connection.

As previously mentioned I have a server side process that periodically checks the status of a given set of services.  To broadcast the latest status I need to broadcast a message to the clients from outside the hub.

SignalR provides exactly this functionality by allowing you to retrieve the currently connected clients for a given hub by calling Hub.GetClients<T> where T is the hub you wish to retrieve the clients for.

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
public class HealthMonitor
{
    public void Check()
    {
        /*
         * code ommited for clarity, 
         * but some process running on say a timer
         * or scheduler returns the latest state of the 
         * services and updates the messages
         * property on the HealthCheck hub
         */

        dynamic clients = Hub.GetClients<HealthCheck>();
        clients.updateMessages(HealthCheck.Messages);
    }
}
[/sourcecode]

The code above is a arbitrary piece of code which can be run on the server. It can however also broadcast a message to all the currently connected clients outside of the hub itself.  The other code change I made was to change the messages field variable to a property so I can keep the same list in sync whether it is updated from a client or server request.

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
public class HealthCheck : Hub
{
    private static List<string> messages;

    public static List<String> Messages 
    { 
        get
        {
            if (messages == null)
            {
                messages = new List<string>();
            }

            return messages;
        }
        set
        {
           messages = value;
        }
    }

//remaining code ommited
[/sourcecode]

Each request that is received within the hub also includes the callers context.  This can be used to only broadcast a response to a specific client.  SignalR also provides the functionality to alternatively broadcast a response to a group of subscribers.   

It is worth pointing out that the client is not restricted to being an MVC view, it can also be a .NET client.  

SignalR is open source framework hosted on github.  I would strongly recommend having a look at the documentation on the <a href="https://github.com/SignalR/SignalR/wiki">github site</a>.

The project I am currently working on has about seven-hundered unit tests.  On previous projects I have worked on, there have been as many as two-thousand tests. Unit tests are definitely not just for Christmas, they are for the lifetime of the code base! They have a purpose and that is to minmise bugs being checked into source control.  Unit tests are also meant to act as documentation of the code.  I have a rule that if I cannot understand what a particular unit test is trying to do in thirty seconds, then it needs to be refactored!  Generally the tests that I cannot make sense of are due to noise around the test and the test class itself.

This blog post aims to introduce three guidelines to help improve the maintainability and readability of your unit tests, by 
<ol>
    <li>altering the layout of your test classes</li> 
    <li>reducing common noise</li> 
    <li>and improving readability</li>
</ol>  
I have introduced these three guidelines recently into my team and have found that the quality and understanding of each test has greatly improved, in particular when refactoring or fixing bugs in existing classes.
<br/>
1) <b>Structuring Unit Tests</b>
When unit testing properly, most public methods within an application will have multiple unit tests associated to it. These tests should cover the different outputs to a method based usually on a different set of input data.  Given a class under test with a lot of public methods, the test class can quite often become quite overloaded and quite difficult without close inspection to see what each test method is actually testing, i.e. the method it is testing and the scenarios for which it is under test.  

With this in mind I recently read a post by <a href="http://haacked.com/archive/2012/01/02/structuring-unit-tests.aspx" target="_blank">Phil Haack</a> detailing a solution he had come across to improve the readability of what each test class is actually doing.  The solution is simple.  For each public method you are testing, in your unit test class, create a nested class to encapsulate all the test methods for a given method.  This is effectively grouping together tests by public method.  This may seem like overkill at first, but to avoid repetition, you can define the setup and teardown methods in the base class.  This means all the nested classes can inherit the base to reuse anything that should be shared. 

The following example below shows the basic structure of a test class, which tests two public methods, the first called Get, the second Post.


[sourcecode language="csharp"]

    [TestClass]
    public class BlogPostTaskTests
    {
        protected Mock<IBlogPostRepository> blogPostRepository;

        [TestInitialize]
        public void Setup()
        {
            //shared setup, generally just initialising mocks
        }

        [TestClass]
        public class TheGetMethod : BlogPostTaskTests
        {
            [TestMethod]
            public void HappyPath()
            {
                //arrange
                //act
                //assert
            }

            [TestMethod]
            public void UnhappyPath()
            {
                //arrange
                //act
                //assert
            }
        }

        [TestClass]
        public class ThePostMethod : BlogPostTaskTests
        {
            [TestMethod]
            public void HappyPath()
            {
                //arrange
                //act
                //assert
            }

            //Additional Tests for the Post method here
        }

        [TestCleanup]
        public void Cleanup()
        {
        }
    }

[/sourcecode]
<br/>
2) <b>Use the Test Data Builder Pattern for test data</b>
Most unit tests require some input data for a method to test, and some output data to assert.  I have found it too commonly the case that developers will duplicate instances of objects across multiple test classes, and initialise the object with hard coded test values. All this set up code within a test class adds a lot of noise to test classes which can make it difficult to understand what the test is doing.

Given the following class:

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
public class BlogPost
{
    public int Id { get; set; }

    public string Title { get; set; }

    public string Content { get; set; }
}
[/sourcecode]

All to commonly you will find scattered across many test classes an instance of this class being initialised with test values to be used in a test. 

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
var blogPost = new BlogPost
{
    Id = 1,
    Title = "My Title",
    Content = "My Content"
};
[/sourcecode]

Following the DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle, I would recommend having a look at the test data builder pattern.  The code below is an example of this for the BlogPost class.  The class follows a number of conventions for consistency

<ul>
    <li>Create a class for each domain object.  The name of the class follows [DomainName]Builder</li>
    <li>A private member variable for each property on the underlining class is added.  This variable is assigned a default value.</li>
    <li>To allow you to override a default value, provide a method with the name With[PropertyName].  This method follows a fluent style to allow you to chain methods together.  Only add the With methods when you need them.  95% of the time the default value will probably suffice, there is no value in adding code that is not ever executed.</li>
    <li>Add a Build method.  This method will create and return a new instance of the object with either the default or overrided values.</li>
</ul>

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
public class BlogPostBuilder
{
    private int id = new Random().Next(1000);
    private string title = "My Title";
    private string content = "My Content";

    public BlogPostBuilder WithTitle(string title)
    {
        this.title = title;
        return this;
    }

    public BlogPost Build()
    {
        return new BlogPost
        {
            Id = id,
            Title = title,
            Content = content
        };
    }
}
[/sourcecode]

An example of using the builder class

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
 var blogPost = new BlogPostBuilder()
                                    .WithTitle("Another Title")
                                    .Build();
[/sourcecode]

Each unit test method should be responsible for initializing its own test data opposed to initializing the test data within the test setup.  This makes it clear what data each unit test it utilising. 
<br/>
3) <b>Use unit testing extension plugins to improve readability</b>
I have recently been looking a very useful library called Fluent Assertions which provide extensions on top of unit testing frameworks such, with the aim of improving readability by following a more natural language, and reducing the amount of code that is required.  

Fluent Assertions is effectively a set of extension methods on top of commonly used unit testing frameworks  such as NUnit and MSTest.  

As a simple example you could take the following Assert statement:

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
Assert.IsTrue(actualOutcome > 5);
[/sourcecode]

and rewrite it as the follows:

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
actualOutcome .Should().BeGreaterOrEqualTo(5);
[/sourcecode]

This is a simple example, but Fluent Assertions provides a wealth of extensions.  

You can download Fluent Assertions via NuGet with the following command from the package manager console within Visual Studio.

<blockquote>
INSTALL-PACKAGE FluentAssertions
</blockquote>

and you can read about it <a href="http://fluentassertions.codeplex.com/" target="_blank">here</a> 
<br/s>
I would recommend next time you write some tests, try following the three guideline above, I guarentee it will improve the maintainability and readability of your tests. 

I would be very interested to hear any guidelines you follow to improve your unit tests.  Thanks for reading.

